{"id":"1609.01705","submitter":"Bhargav Narayanan","authors":"Bhargav Narayanan, Julian Sahasrabudhe, Istv\\'an Tomon","title":"Ramsey graphs induce subgraphs of many different sizes","comments":"24 pages, Combinatorica","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A graph on $n$ vertices is said to be \\emph{$C$-Ramsey} if every clique or\nindependent set of the graph has size at most $C \\log n$. The only known\nconstructions of Ramsey graphs are probabilistic in nature, and it is generally\nbelieved that such graphs possess many of the same properties as dense random\ngraphs. Here, we demonstrate one such property: for any fixed $C>0$, every\n$C$-Ramsey graph on $n$ vertices induces subgraphs of at least $n^{2-o(1)}$\ndistinct sizes. This near-optimal result is closely related to two unresolved\nconjectures, the first due to Erd\\H{o}s and McKay and the second due to\nErd\\H{o}s, Faudree and S\\'{o}s, both from 1992.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Sep 2016 19:40:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Sep 2016 13:16:14 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 7 Sep 2017 12:42:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-09-08"}
